{"timestamp": "2025-11-29 17:04:46.173252", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network state summary and findings\n\nExecutive summary\n- The network has a clear isolation problem affecting the 10.2.1.0/24 host segment (host_2_1_1_1). The host has no IP address and cannot reach the datacenter/server networks (10.200.0.0/24) or the DHCP server.\n- The distribution router for that segment (router_dist_2_1) is up at the interface level but is not learning/advertising remote routes via OSPF (no OSPF adjacency), so it cannot reach the DHCP/server networks. This appears to be an OSPF configuration problem (area mismatch).\n- Secondary/related anomalies: several hosts in the 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_*) show inability to reach 10.200.0.2 (DNS) and other 10.200.0.0/24 addresses — this looks like inter-subnet routing asymmetry or policy affecting the 20.x -> 10.200.0.x path and should be investigated further.\n\nEvidence and key observations (raw findings)\n1) Host host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.x segment)\n- Reachability: host_2_1_1_1 -> many destinations = 100% packet loss (e.g., to host_1_1_1_1, dhcp_server, load_balancer, all web servers).\n- Host net config (ifconfig / ip addr) shows eth0 has NO IPv4 address configured:\n  - ifconfig eth0 shows UP but no \"inet ...\" line\n  - ip route on host returned empty (no default or subnet route)\n- Interpretation: host_2_1_1_1 failed to obtain DHCP configuration (or lost it). That explains total loss from that host to network services.\n\n2) router_dist_2_1 (distribution router for 10.2.1.0/24)\n- Interface/status:\n  - br0: 10.2.1.1/24 (connected) — the router has the correct local addressing for the access VLAN.\n  - eth0: 172.16.0.9/31 — link to core present (ping from router_core_2 to router_dist_2_1 succeeds).\n- Routing: frr_show_ip_route shows only local connected routes (10.2.1.0/24 and 172.16.0.8/31). There are no learned remote routes to 10.200.0.0/24 or to the DHCP server.\n- Ping test: router_dist_2_1 -> dhcp_server returned \"connect: Network is unreachable\" (no route to 10.200.0.8).\n- OSPF status (router_dist_2_1): reports \"Number of areas attached to this router: 1\" but that area is listed as Area ID: 0.0.0.66 and \"Number of fully adjacent neighbors in this area: 0\".\n  - In other words: router_dist_2_1 is running OSPF in an unexpected/incorrect area (0.0.0.66) and has no OSPF adjacency with the core routers, so it does not receive OSPF-learned routes.\n\n3) Core / server-side check (control/comparison)\n- server_access_router and router_core_2 show normal route entries for the server networks:\n  - server_access_router has 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected and OSPF routes for other areas (so the server side is reachable from the cores).\n  - router_core_2’s OSPF shows normal adjacencies and LSAs (it is an ABR).\n- Ping tests:\n  - server_access_router -> dhcp_server OK (4/4).\n  - router_core_2 -> router_dist_2_1 OK (4/4). This confirms L2/IP connectivity between the distribution router and the core but OSPF adjacency still absent.\n\n4) Inter-server/backend anomalies (secondary)\n- Several backend_web_* hosts (addresses in 20.200.0.x) show 100% loss to dns_server (10.200.0.2) and to some 10.200.0.x hosts, while other 10.200.0.x servers (web_server_0..3, load_balancer) have mutual connectivity and can reach dns_server.\n- Examples:\n  - backend_web_2 -> dns_server = down.\n  - backend_web_2 -> load_balancer = ok.\n  - backend_web_1 / backend_web_0 show similar asymmetric reachability to 10.200.0.2.\n- This indicates selective routing or policy issues for the 20.200.0.0/24 -> 10.200.0.0/24 path (or possibly ACLs/firewall or missing route advertisement for the 20.200.0.x networks on some routers). This needs a separate focused investigation.\n\nLocalization: faulty devices/elements\n- Primary faulty device: router_dist_2_1\n  - Symptoms located here: OSPF area mismatch (area 0.0.0.66), no OSPF neighbors, missing learned routes to datacenter/DHCP, ping to DHCP server returns \"Network is unreachable\".\n- Affected endpoints:\n  - host_2_1_1_1: no IPv4 address (did not get DHCP) and thus isolated — symptom, but root cause is upstream routing/DHCP reachability problem.\n- Secondary areas to investigate:\n  - Any router(s) responsible for routing the 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web) to 10.200.0.0/24 — evidence shows backend_web_* -> dns_server failing while other 10.200 hosts are fine. Candidate devices: server_access_router or FRR config that advertises backend networks.\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis (supported by evidence)\n- The immediate root cause for the 10.2.1.0/24 outage and host_2_1_1_1 isolation is a routing/OSPF configuration issue on router_dist_2_1:\n  - router_dist_2_1 is configured in a different OSPF area (0.0.0.66) than the core/expected area(s), so it did not form OSPF adjacency with the core routers.\n  - Because OSPF adjacency is absent, router_dist_2_1 has only local connected routes and lacks paths to the DHCP server and datacenter networks (10.200.0.0/24).\n  - As a result the DHCP relay/requests from host_2_1_1_1 cannot reach the central DHCP server, so the host has no IP address and is fully isolated.\n- The inter-subnet problems seen for backend_web_* -> dns_server likely stem from a separate routing/policy issue (missing route advertisement or ACL affecting 20.200.0.0/24 towards 10.200.0.0/24). This is distinct from the dist_2_1 OSPF-area problem but should be investigated after resolving OSPF adjacency.\n\nRelevant supporting outputs (highlights)\n- host_2_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip: eth0 present but no \"inet ...\" — host has no IPv4 address and ip route shows nothing.\n- router_dist_2_1 ip_route: only shows 10.2.1.0/24 and 172.16.0.8/31 (no routes to 10.200.0.0/24).\n- router_dist_2_1 OSPF conf: Area ID: 0.0.0.66 and \"Number of fully adjacent neighbors in this area: 0\".\n- router_dist_2_1 -> dhcp_server ping: \"Network is unreachable\".\n- server_access_router -> dhcp_server ping: successful (server sid